<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>⚡ WD002 Week 3 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Events — Reacting to the User · <strong>Course:</strong> Web Dev Basics: JavaScript · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week your page <strong>listens</strong>. An <em>event</em> is something the user does — a click, a hover, a key press. <code>addEventListener("click", ...)</code> runs a function when that event happens. You will build a score counter that goes up, down, and resets.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Before you run it, write what you think will happen.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button id=&quot;btn&quot;&gt;Tap&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#btn&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    console.log(&quot;tapped&quot;);
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What prints when you click the button </strong>three<strong> times?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;span id=&quot;score&quot;&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;up&quot;&gt;+1&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  let score = 0;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#up&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    score = score + 1;
    document.querySelector(&quot;#score&quot;).textContent = score;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>You click <code>+1</code> four times. What number is on the screen?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button id=&quot;reset&quot;&gt;Reset&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  let score = 10;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#reset&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    score = 0;
    document.querySelector(&quot;#score&quot;).textContent = score;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The score starts at 10. After clicking reset, what is it?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button id=&quot;down&quot;&gt;-1&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  let score = 2;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#down&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    score = score - 1;
    document.querySelector(&quot;#score&quot;).textContent = score;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>You click <code>-1</code> five times starting from 2. What number shows? Is anything strange about it?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, then rewrite it so it works. After that, explain why the original was wrong and why your fix works.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Clicking the button should add 1 to the score on screen. Right now the number on screen never changes, even though the click happens.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;span id=&quot;score&quot;&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;up&quot;&gt;+1&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  let score = 0;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#up&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    score = score + 1;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the variable goes up, but nobody updates the screen. One line is missing.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should listen for a <strong>click</strong>. Right now clicking the button does nothing.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button id=&quot;go&quot;&gt;Go&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#go&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;clik&quot;, function() {
    console.log(&quot;go!&quot;);
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the event name is misspelled, so the browser is listening for an event that never happens.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The score should never drop below 0. Right now clicking <code>-1</code> past zero gives negative numbers.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button id=&quot;down&quot;&gt;-1&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  let score = 0;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#down&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    score = score - 1;
    document.querySelector(&quot;#score&quot;).textContent = score;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> before subtracting, check whether the score is already 0. Use an <code>if</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Make It Yours 📸</h2>
<p>Build a score counter with <strong>three</strong> buttons: <code>+1</code>, <code>-1</code>, and <code>reset</code>.</p>
<ol>
<li>Show the score somewhere on the page.</li>
<li>Use <code>addEventListener</code> to connect each button to its own job.</li>
<li><code>+1</code> adds, <code>-1</code> subtracts, <code>reset</code> sets the score back to 0.</li>
<li>Make sure the score <strong>never goes below 0</strong> (use an <code>if</code>).</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Stretch:</strong> add a <code>+5</code> button, or change the page color when the score reaches a certain number.</p>
<p>When you finish, come back here. Send a <strong>photo or video</strong> of all three buttons working, then explain what you did. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>First, I made buttons for …</p>
<p>I used <code>addEventListener</code> to …</p>
<p>To stop the score going below 0, I …</p>
<p>The reset button works by …</p>
<p>One tricky moment was when …</p>
<p>If I had more time, I would …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Record Your Walkthrough 🎥</h2>
<p>Take a video on your phone (or a parent's phone) while your counter runs. Talk through it like you are teaching someone who has never seen it. Try to use these words: <strong>event</strong>, <strong>listener</strong>, <strong>click</strong>, <strong>score</strong>, <strong>reset</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show the counter at 0.</li>
<li>Click <code>+1</code> a few times, then <code>-1</code>, then <code>reset</code>.</li>
<li>Read one listener out loud and say which button it belongs to.</li>
<li>Show what happens when you try to go below 0.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Write what you will say in your video.</strong> Plan it here before you record — you can read from it while filming.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

